<br>
For pure contentment, though, there's nothing for me like reading a smart fantasy.  Lucifer is one of the best I've read so far, but its serial nature is driving me batty.  I'd love some recommendations for lit that provides a similar buzz.<br>
<br>
For me, some authors who create appealing RIYLs vis a vis Lucifer (besides Mr. Gaiman) are Tim Powers, China Mieville, Neal Stephenson, Jerry Jay Carroll, William Browning Spencer, Michael Swanwick, Umberto Eco, Christopher Priest, Geoff Ryman, Iain Banks.<br>
<br>
I'm a little rushed right now or I'd provide a listing of specific titles by those authors that I recommend (and maybe an enticing summary for each).  I hope to come back soon and do just that.<br>
<br>
I'm also hoping one or two of you fascinating creatures has a little nugget to throw my way so I can while away some hours in between pacing the floor waiting for Inferno and Lucifer vol. 5.<br>
<br>
Meantime, I'll go back to puttering in the purlieu.<br>
