<br>
Tim Powers: Appealing melanges of fact and fantasy illuminating a secret history of the world, with loose conceptual links between many (but not all) of his novels.  Generally fast-paced, with a a good mixture action, the supernatural, suspense, and complex characters struggling with moral dilemmas.  HIs greatest weakness is occasional lapses into anachronistic dialogue and the general far-fetchedness of his plots (although that's hasn't been a strong deterrent to me, since his books move so breathlessly you don't have much time to ask WTF?).<br>
<br>
The Drawing of the Dark -- In 1529 amidst the siege of Vienna, a struggle for control of a mystically powerful ale is at the heart of the larger struggle between East and West. First appearance of the Fisher King mythos in his books.  One of my favorites.  Nice pun in the title is also the start of a Powers tendency.<br>
<br>
The Anubis Gates -- This one has got it all.  Prototypical Powers, and my favorite whenever I'm not thinking about some other Powers book.<br>
<br>
From the cover:<br>
<br>
&quot;An ancient Egyptian sorcerer whose powerful magic can change the history of the entire world!<br>
A modern millionaire with a sinister plan who journeys back to England in 1810!<br>
A werewolf who switches bodies - then kills his victims to keep his identity a secret!<br>
A hideously deformed clown of crime who performs grotesque experiments on his victims!<br>
A brainwashed Lord Byron - programmed to kill King George!<br>
A young woman disguised as a boy, hunting the thing that killed her lover!<br>
And our hero, Professor Brendan Doyle, who has no idea what he is getting into when he agrees to give a lecture on Samuel Taylor Coleridge...&quot; <br>
<br>
On Stranger Tides -- Pirates and the struggle for control of the fountain of youth.  My only regret is that he didn't find some way to weave monkeys and robots into his yarn.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Dinner at Deviant's Palace -- Somewhat of a departure -- an itinerant musician in a post-apocalyptic SoCal is trying to find himself while runninbg away as fast as he can and stalked by his own shadow.  More like traditional sci-fi in setting than his other books, but right in line with his standard themes.<br>
<br>
The Stress of Her Regard -- More Romantic poets, this time around struggling to escape their muse who is extracting a terrible price from those close to them.  Weaving various threads such as lamia and nephillim into another secret history document.<br>
<br>
Last Call, Expiration Date, Earthquake Weather -- <br>
3 linked novels telling the story of the Fisher King in America leading to a climactic transfer of power in present-day SoCal.  Mixes gambling in Vegas, vineyards and Dionysus, randomness, Thomas Edison, earthquakes and more in a sprawling tale which, as is often the case with such things, lacks a little of the punch of Powers' more stand-alone books, but is still highly recommended.  Read something else by him first, and you'll know if you want to tackle this.  If you like something else by him this will be worth the effort.<br>
<br>
Declare -- The story of the occult forces behind the cold war.  Weaves in Kim Philby as villain/foil, with plenty of cryptology (an unexpected focus of millennial gestalt to me) and djinn.  Not as wild as some of his earlier work, and with little of the supernatural for the first fifty pages or so, it took me three tries to get into this.  By the time I finished it I loved though.  <br>
<br>
Well, that's all for Mr. P.  As you can tell, I quite like him.  I think the striking thing about his work is that he can touch on many historical and intellectual themes in what are essentially light-hearted quick reading adventure novels (though not without character growth and development or moral struggles), and he doesn't come off, to me at least, as a mere show-off.  Then again, he's no match in the intellect and heavyosity department for his namesake Richard.  But for those of who reside somewhere between Richard and Austin, a pleasant companion by the fireside or on the beach.<br>
<br>
I'll finish up with a couple few proposed author additions to my list:<br>
<br>
Richard Grant, John Crowley, Robert Holdstock.<br>
<br>
Hope you find something you enjoy; and if my list (or choice of Powers to open with) is presumptious or too obvious for you denizens of Lightbringer, I look forward to you firing away with something to broaden my horizons.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 68<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(11/6/03 5:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: RIYL Lucifer</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Anubis Gates</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (1983) won the 1984 Philip K. Dick award, in case anyone's interested. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm11.showPrevMessage?topicID=9.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm11.showNextMessage?topicID=9.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=9.topic&index=2><img src=http://lightbringer.mattpeckham.com/pics/add_reply.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm11.emailToFriend?topicID=9.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm11.threadControl?topicID=9